				<h2 style="color: grey">A comedian does stand-up with Death.</h2>
				<h3><a class="smallertitle">This night felt a bit different for Dave. His jokes were landing, but he felt off. It didn't help that the green room smelled faintly of vomit. He coudn't wait for the intermission to be over, for the night to be over. Even prior to the intermission he knew something didn't feel right. Dave didn't get cold feet and neither did he get nervous; he quite simply wasn't feeling it, like an athlete stepping onto the pitch not wanting to win. He felt like it didn't matter; he felt like nothing mattered.
					Dave walked back on stage. The audience greeted him with hesitant applause. Better than usual, he thought.
					The lights were suddenly bright. And then, a pain in his right arm, a pain in his chest, the lights now blinding, the sounds of the audience gone. He fell to the ground, knocking over the microphone stand with a thunderous noise. When he came to he was staring at a black shoes. No ankles, but pants and a suit hovered above them. His head was throbbing and he was still on the stage and the audience was in their seats, motionless. Colorless. Silent. They were frozen in time. A gloved hand appeared before him. Except there was no wrist here either. "Get up, Dave. You're dead but not gone."
					</a>
				</h3>
